</p>
<p>
If the endpoints of a segment are moved along two intersecting lines, a fix=
ed point on the segment (or on the line that prolongs it) describes an arc =
of an ellipse. This is known as the trammel construction of an ellipse (Eve=
s 1965, p.&nbsp;177).
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/gifs/EllipticGears.gif" cl=
ass=3D"" style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"245" alt=3D"Ell=
iptic gears">
</div>
<p>
It is possible to construct elliptical gears that rotate smoothly against o=
ne another (Brown 1871, pp.&nbsp;14-15; Reuleaux and Kennedy 1876, p.&nbsp;=
70; Clark and Downward 1930; KMODDL).
</p>
<p>
The ellipse was first studied by Menaechmus, investigated by Euclid, and na=
med by Apollonius. The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Focus.html"=
>focus</a> and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ConicSectionDirectr=
ix.html">conic
 section directrix</a> of an ellipse were considered by Pappus. In 1602, Ke=
pler believed
 that the orbit of Mars was <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Oval.h=
tml">oval</a>; he later discovered that
 it was an ellipse with the Sun at one <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/Focus.html">focus</a>. In fact, Kepler
 introduced the word "<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Focus.html">=
focus</a>" and published his
 discovery in 1609. In 1705 Halley showed that the comet now named after hi=
m moved
 in an elliptical orbit around the Sun (MacTutor Archive). An ellipse rotat=
ed about
 its minor axis gives an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/OblateSph=
eroid.html">oblate spheroid</a>, while
 an ellipse rotated about its major axis gives a <a href=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/ProlateSpheroid.html">prolate
 spheroid</a>.
</p>
<p>
A ray of light passing through a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/F=
ocus.html">focus</a> will pass through the other focus after a single bounc=
e (Hilbert and Cohn-Vossen 1999, p.&nbsp;3).
 Reflections not passing through a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com=
/Focus.html">focus</a> will be tangent
 to a confocal <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Hyperbola.html">hyp=
erbola</a> or ellipse, depending on whether
 the ray passes between the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Focus.=
html">foci</a> or not.
</p>
