<p>
The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Locus.html">locus</a> of the a=
pex of a variable <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Cone.html">cone<=
/a> containing an ellipse fixed in three-space is a <a href=3D"https://math=
world.wolfram.com/Hyperbola.html">hyperbola</a>
 through the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Focus.html">foci</a> =
of the ellipse. In addition, the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/L=
ocus.html">locus</a>
 of the apex of a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Cone.html">cone<=
/a> containing that <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Hyperbola.html=
">hyperbola</a>
 is the original ellipse. Furthermore, the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wol=
fram.com/Eccentricity.html">eccentricities</a>
 of the ellipse and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Hyperbola.html=
">hyperbola</a> are reciprocals. The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.c=
om/Locus.html">locus</a> of centers of a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfr=
am.com/PappusChain.html">Pappus chain</a>
 of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Circle.html">circles</a> is an=
 ellipse. Surprisingly, the locus of the
 end of a garage door mounted on rollers along a vertical track but extendi=
ng beyond
 the track is a quadrant of an ellipse (Wells 1991, p.&nbsp;66). (The <a hr=
ef=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Envelope.html">envelope</a>
 of the door's positions is an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Ast=
roid.html">astroid</a>.)
</p>
